# Flutter Riverpod + Isar Boilerplate Rules

## Tech Stack
- Flutter & Dart (Production-Ready, Modern syntax)
- State Management: Riverpod (with riverpod_generator code generation)
- Local Database: isar_community (with isar_generator)

## Architecture Style
- Feature-First layered structure inside `lib/features/[feature_name]/`
- Layers inside each feature MUST be strictly separated:
  - `domain/` (entities, abstract repositories) - Pure Dart, NO external frameworks.
  - `data/` (models, mappers, repository implementations, Isar collections).
  - `presentation/` (screens, widgets, riverpod providers/notifiers).

## Coding Standards & Patterns
- ALWAYS use Riverpod code generation (`@riverpod` or `@Riverpod(keepAlive: true)`).
- NO manual state mutation (`state = ...`) inside CRUD methods if state is stream-driven.
- Database streams must use reactive binding. State updates automatically from the database observer.
- ALWAYS cancel stream subscriptions using `ref.onDispose(subscription.cancel)`.
- Isar instances initialization must prevent dual-open errors: use `Isar.getInstance() ?? await Isar.open(...)`.
- Prefer immutable data types for Domain Entities.

## Code Generation Command
- Before asking to run the project, ensure code generation is executed via:
  `dart run build_runner build --delete-conflicting-outputs`